description.narrative: COs and partners have enhanced capacity to contribute to at-scale design and delivery of evidence-informed programmes for the prevention and treatment of malnutrition from pregnancy to adolescence., which contributes to Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition (Covid), Technical Excellence In Policy And Programmes. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Comprehensive, sustainable and enabling environment that leaves no child behind is supported by policies, programmes, strategies, budgets and actions of Governments, regional institutions, private sector, media, financial institutions, UN and UNICEF country programmes in South Asia, in development and humanitarian contexts.

description.narrative: The number of children under five affected by stunted growth in South Asia has declined from 57.4 million in 2018 to 53.8 million in 2020. However, the progress is currently insufficient to achieve the headline result on stunting and is not shared equally among countries in the region. The protracted Covid-19 pandemic and its socio-economic impacts continue to compound the vulnerability of children to malnutrition and threatens to unravel years of progress towards the regional headline result on stunting. Improving maternal nutrition and children’s diets in early life remain key programme priorities for achieving progress towards the headline result. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:20/12/2021
